
Paris, 20 March 1780. RC in John Thaxters hand (PCC, No. 84, I, f. 337338). LbC (Adams Papers); notation: No. 22 delivered Mr. Izard. printed: Wharton, ed., Dipl. Corr. Amer. Rev., 3:561.
With this letter, read in Congress on 1 Aug., John Adams sent copies of the London General Advertiser and the London Morning Post. The newspapers, which he promised to send regularly and had received from Edm Jacques Genet (see JA to Genet, 22 March, note 1, below), represented the views of the opposition and the ministry respectively. He also commented on the disputes between the various factions in Great Britain, a probable delay in the sailing of Rochambeaus army, and Lafayettes return to America.
